1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:04,342
Titanic had enough lifeboats to satisfy the

2
00:00:04,342 --> 00:00:05,653
law.

3
00:00:06,434 --> 00:00:07,714
That sentence sounds safe.

4
00:00:08,575 --> 00:00:11,337
In 1912, it was the problem.

5
00:00:12,619 --> 00:00:15,002
British rules measured lifeboats by tonnage.

6
00:00:15,882 --> 00:00:18,934
Above 10,000 tons, the top bracket required

7
00:00:18,934 --> 00:00:21,987
16 lifeboats for 990 people.

8
00:00:22,888 --> 00:00:26,192
Titanic carried 16 lifeboats and four collapsibles,

9
00:00:26,192 --> 00:00:29,495
enough for about 1,176 people.

10
00:00:30,396 --> 00:00:33,038
More than 2,200 were aboard.

11
00:00:33,018 --> 00:00:34,580
The paperwork said compliant.

12
00:00:35,262 --> 00:00:36,363
The ship said otherwise.

13
00:00:37,164 --> 00:00:38,527
Some boats left underfilled.

14
00:00:39,189 --> 00:00:40,231
The law failed one way.

15
00:00:40,832 --> 00:00:42,234
Evacuation failed another.

16
00:00:43,316 --> 00:00:45,500
Afterward, investigators pushed the correction.

17
00:00:46,161 --> 00:00:48,304
Count people carried, not tonnage.

18
00:00:49,347 --> 00:00:51,431
Two years later, SOLAS turned that lesson

19
00:00:51,431 --> 00:00:53,514
into international rulemaking.

20
00:00:54,375 --> 00:00:56,279
The old category kept measuring yesterday's ship

21
00:00:56,279 --> 00:00:58,182
while approving tomorrow's risk.

22
00:00:58,984 --> 00:01:02,350
Small causes, massive consequences.
